# Line endings policy.
#
# git-on-Windows defaults to `core.autocrlf=true`, which translates LF
# in the repo to CRLF on checkout. That's fine for prose / hand-edited
# code, but TOXIC for files that get parsed by external tools that
# expect LF specifically — sqlc 1.29 in particular mis-tokenizes
# queries when the source file has CRLF, producing truncated SQL
# strings and missing parameters in the generated Go (we hit this
# 2026-04-30 trying to add new federation queries).
#
# `text=auto` here lets git keep auto-detection on, but the explicit
# `eol=lf` overrides defeat the Windows CRLF conversion for the file
# types that need it.
#
# After committing this file, on Windows clones run:
#   git rm --cached -r .
#   git reset --hard
# to renormalise the working tree. Or just delete + re-checkout the
# affected files.

* text=auto

# SQL files are consumed by sqlc + goose. Both tools' parsers expect LF.
*.sql       text eol=lf

# Go source/codegen — `gofmt` emits LF and the toolchain barfs on CRLF
# in some cases. Lock it down.
*.go        text eol=lf

# YAML configs (sqlc.yaml, hubplay.yaml, OpenAPI spec, GitHub workflows).
*.yaml      text eol=lf
*.yml       text eol=lf

# Shell scripts must be LF or `sh`/`bash` rejects them with cryptic
# `: not found` errors on the shebang line.
*.sh        text eol=lf

# Windows-only files (Powershell, .bat) keep their native CRLF.
*.ps1       text eol=crlf
*.bat       text eol=crlf
*.cmd       text eol=crlf

# Binary lockfiles — never touch.
*.png       binary
*.jpg       binary
*.jpeg      binary
*.webp      binary
*.ico       binary
*.gif       binary
*.pdf       binary
